{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523432","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523432"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:55:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:55:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13897"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13897","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13897"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.26,0.28,0.13,0.24]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6516"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111782"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6516","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6516"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13897"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93852"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"1111"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13008"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14608"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45738"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111782","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111782"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old man is currently on the ward recovering from a chest infection. He has been making good progress, but over the past four hours he has become quite hostile with staff members; he has become verbally aggressive to nurses and doctors, threatening to stab them if they try to insert a cannula. When the staff members attempt to talk clearly to the patient to calm him down, he attempts to physically assault them. He seems confused, and does not appear aware of where he currently is.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrior to all of this occurring, the patient was quite calm and there was no history of aggression or behaviour problems. This is all occurring on a background of Parkinson\u0027s disease, hypertension, and recurrent urinary tract infections secondary to benign prostatic hypertrophy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBased on the risk posed by the patient, it has been deemed necessary to use pharmacological management to address the patient\u0027s aggressiveness.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications is most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Olanzapine","Haloperidol","Quetiapine","Risperidone","Diazepam"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this question, the patient is showing signs of\u003Cstrong\u003E delirium\u003C/strong\u003E. Delirium entails a short term change in cognition that may result in confusion, an inability to focus, problems with memory and agitation and aggression (which is occurring in this case). This occurs as a result of a medical condition that predisposes the patient to potential cognitive changes. Risk factors for delirium include infections (such as those in the urinary tract, but also in other locations such as pneumonia and meningitis), drug withdrawal, hypoxia, trauma, and shock.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of delirium will vary depending on the cause, but in general, in entails placing a priority on addressing the underlying cause, maintaining fluid status, and ensuring that the patient does not pose a risk to themselves or others. If a patient is behaving aggressively, the first course of action would be to talk to them and to try to calm them down. However, if this is unsuccessful, then antipsychotic medications may be utilised.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOf high pertinence is that the fact that this patient has Parkinson\u0027s disease, as this has major implications on treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaloperidol \u003C/strong\u003Eis not recommended for the treatment of psychosis in Parkinson\u0027s disease patients as this drug can cause extra-pyramidal side effects such as dystonia and Parkinsonism - hence bradykinesia, resting tremor and cogwheel rigidity. Similarly, \u003Cstrong\u003Erisperidone \u003C/strong\u003Eand \u003Cstrong\u003Eolanzapine \u003C/strong\u003Ecan cause comparable side effects. Note that, for patients who do not have Parkinson\u0027s, each of the aforementioned treatments may be considered to address aggression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EQuetiapine\u003C/strong\u003E is an atypical antipsychotic that has been shown to be effective in improving delirium/agitation in Parkinson\u0027s disease patients. Importantly, this drug is well tolerated in Parkinson\u0027s disease patients compared to other drugs, and does not result in worsening of cognitive and motor symptoms in the way that other anti-psychotics tend to. This is the medication that should be given to this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiazepam \u003C/strong\u003Eis a benzodiazepine that is used to treat delirium in alcohol withdrawal. It is not typically recommended for treating delirium from other causes, as it can exacerbate the delirium.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Delirium entails a short term change in cognition that may result in confusion, an inability to focus, problems with memory and agitation and aggression.","Quetiapine is an atypical antipsychotic that may be used to treat aggression for patients with Parkinson\u0027s disease. While haloperidol, risperidone, and olanzapine may be recommended for other aggressive patients with delirium - they are not recommended for Parkinson\u0027s disease patients as they may exacerbate motor and cognitive symptoms."],"references":["Wynn J, Homewood D, Tse V, Fong E, Roberts MJ, Chung E, Dowling C. What to do about recurrent urinary tract infections: A review of evidence behind emerging therapies. Aust J Gen Pract. 2024 May;53(5):265-273. doi: 10.31128/AJGP-10-23-7004. PMID: 38697057.","Li Y, Ma J, Jin Y, Li N, Zheng R, Mu W, Wang J, Si JH, Chen J, Shang HC. Benzodiazepines for treatment of patients with delirium excluding those who are cared for in an intensive care unit. Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2020 Feb 28;2(2):CD012670. doi: 10.1002/14651858.CD012670.pub2. PMID: 32108325; PMCID: PMC7047222.","Shrimanker I, Tadi P, Schoo C, et al. Parkinsonism. [Updated 2024 Mar 13]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK542224/","Chyou TY, Nishtala R, Nishtala PS. Comparative risk of Parkinsonism associated with olanzapine, risperidone and quetiapine in older adults-a propensity score matched cohort study. Pharmacoepidemiol Drug Saf. 2020 Jun;29(6):692-700. doi: 10.1002/pds.5007. Epub 2020 Apr 16. PMID: 32301237.","Williams L, Qiu J, Waller S, Tsui D, Griffith J, Fung VS. An approach to acute clinical deterioration in patients with late-stage Parkinson\u0027s disease. Aust J Gen Pract. 2022 Aug;51(8):577-583. doi: 10.31128/AJGP-03-22-6363. PMID: 35908752."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93852"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13897"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93852","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93852"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-19T21:05:45+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-19T21:05:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"it